	"notes": [
		{
			"id": "n59EOjLWa6SgW0KKk",
			"markdown": "Agents are professional problem-solvers who operate in the shadows of society. Spies, bounty hunters, secret police, corporate troubleshooters, intelligence officers, covert operatives, assassins, and similar professionals all fall under this template. Agents rely on perception, tradecraft, deception, and adaptability to complete missions under pressure, often with limited support and incomplete information.\n\nThe Agent is intentionally broad and multidisciplinary. Its skills represent overlapping fields of tradecraft rather than rigid categories of training. Most Agents develop a balance between stealth, social manipulation, investigation, and controlled violence, but different combinations of Advantages and skill emphases can create radically different operatives. Some Agents are social predators who manipulate targets through charm and lies, while others are surveillance experts, hunters, infiltrators, or ruthless deniable assets. In many campaigns, the Agent serves as the party’s scout, infiltrator, information-gatherer, negotiator, or precision problem-solver, using preparation and specialized knowledge to bypass obstacles that brute force cannot solve cleanly.\n\nThe *Infiltrator* is the spy, undercover operative, interrogator, covert investigator, or social chameleon who survives by becoming invisible socially rather than physically. Infiltrators blend into hostile environments long before trouble starts, manipulating people, identities, and expectations to move unseen through enemy territory. They emphasize Stealth, Acting, Fast-Talk, Detect Lies, Observation, Psychology, Shadowing, Holdout, and Disguise, supported by Cultural Adaptability, Smooth Operator, Social Chameleon, Intuition, and Languages. Their lifestyles often encourage disadvantages such as Secret, Compulsive Lying, Trickster, Paranoia, or Loner.\n\nThe *Assassin* covers hitmen, covert eliminators, black-ops killers, ninja-like infiltrators, and deniable operatives. Some Assassins are disciplined professionals carrying out cold assignments, while others are unstable predators, fanatics, or thrill-seekers who thrive on danger and proximity to violence. They concentrate on Stealth, Observation, Holdout, Knife or Guns, Escape, and Poisons, paired with Combat Reflexes, Silence, Flexibility, Daredevil, and Ambidexterity. Common disadvantages include Bloodlust, Callous, Fanaticism, On the Edge, or Overconfidence.\n\nThe *Troubleshooter* fits corporate spies, executive troubleshooters, political operatives, internal security specialists, and white-collar intelligence professionals. Rather than relying on direct confrontation, Troubleshooters solve problems through leverage, bureaucracy, information control, and institutional power. They specialize in Administration, Computer Hacking, Electronics Operation (Security), Research, Current Affairs, Propaganda, Diplomacy, and Law, supported by Patron, Rank, Security Clearance, and Legal Immunity. Their careers frequently produce disadvantages such as Workaholic, Sense of Duty, Secret, Greed, Obsession, or Code of Honor (Professional).\n\nAgents should carefully decide how much emphasis to place on combat ability. A little skill with Guns, Karate, Judo, or Knife is often enough for survival, while heavy investment can produce a dangerous field operative. Most Agents would rather solve problems through preparation, positioning, deception, and precision than through prolonged stand-up fights. Even heavily armed Agents are usually at their best when they control the situation before violence begins."
		}
	]
